m about $59 billion (at the time he got the options) to $650 billion. He ac=
complished those goals within three years, so he got all the options.The $5=
5.8 billon number is pretty arbitrary: It represents how much the options=
=C2=A0would=C2=A0be worth at a Tesla market cap of=C2=A0exactly=C2=A0$650 b=
illion.
  [5]
 In the event, Tesla=E2=80=99s market cap got as high as $1.2 trillion in 2=
021, at which point Musk=E2=80=99s option package was worth more than $100 =
billion. Tesla=E2=80=99s stock closed yesterday at $155.45, for a market ca=
p of about $495 billion, making the options worth something like $40 billio=
n.
  [6]
But at the time they were granted, in 2018, Musk could not extract any mone=
y at all from them. He=E2=80=99d only be able to exercise them if he hit th=
e performance targets, which he hadn=E2=80=99t yet. And because the $23.34 =
strike price of the options was set to be the same as Tesla=E2=80=99s stock=
 price at the time, even exercising the options, in 2018, wouldn=E2=80=99t =
make him a profit: He=E2=80=99d pay $23.34 to get $23.34 worth of stock, wh=
ich he could just do in the open market. The options were worth $0 if=C2=A0=
Tesla maintained the status quo; they=E2=80=99d only be worth anything to M=
usk if it grew a lot.But the options weren=E2=80=99t=C2=A0worth zero, as an=
 economic matter: There was some probability that Tesla=C2=A0would=C2=A0gro=
w and he=E2=80=99d get to exercise the options and make $55.8 billion, or m=
ore, or less. Finance has reasonably well-understood ways to put a single c=
urrent numerical value=C2=A0on=C2=A0this uncertain distribution of potentia=
l future values. Tesla determined that the options were worth about $2.3 bi=
llion at the time Musk got them: There was some chance they=E2=80=99d end u=
p worthless, some chance they=E2=80=99d end up worth $55.8 billion, some ch=
ance they=E2=80=99d end up worth $100 billion or $40 billion or any other n=
onnegative number, but, averaging over all those possibilities, the expecte=
d value was $2.3 billion.
  [7]
If Tesla gave Musk a thing worth $2.3 billion, that was an expense to Tesla=
, which reduced its net income. And so Tesla=E2=80=99s income statements re=
flected that $2.3 billion expense over the period of Musk=E2=80=99s pay pla=
n.
  [8]
Notice that Tesla had an expense of $2.3 billion, while Musk got options th=
at turned out to be worth more than $100 billion at their peak. That=E2=80=
=99s a nice trade, a nice feature of stock-options-based compensation: The =
expense to Tesla turned out to be much lower than the actual value delivere=
d to Musk.
  [9]
=C2=A0Anyway, this January a Delaware judge decided that Musk=E2=80=99s 201=
8 pay package was illegally big, and decreed that the options would vanish.=
